  "findings": [
    "PPL is very high across all three Gemma-4-IT variants on wikitext-2-raw-v1 (range 11896 to 57163). This is the expected 'IT model on raw continuation' signal: the models are instruction-tuned, not base language models, so they score raw-text continuation poorly. Google does not release base weights for Gemma 4. Relative comparisons across variants are still meaningful.",
    "Slot-bank PPL (38957) differs from stock PPL (57163) by ~32% on the same 26B-A4B GGUF \u2014 the Flash-MoE slot-bank path is NOT bit-identical to the stock MoE kernel on Gemma 4. Chunk 1 matches within <1% (5997 stock vs 6030 slot-bank), but subsequent chunks diverge, likely from --moe-prefetch-temporal biasing subsequent routing. Slot-bank is actually LOWER PPL (better) here, which is surprising \u2014 worth investigating whether stock mode is numerically off vs slot-bank's routing is closer to the intended Gemma 4 behavior.",
    "Decode throughput confirms prior measurements: 31B Q8_0 = 14.6 tok/s, 26B-A4B stock fp16 = 50.3 tok/s, 26B-A4B slot-bank fp16 = 8.3 tok/s (6x slowdown from stock, consistent with 95%-IO-bound slot-bank path).",
    "Slot-bank hit rate was 60.5% at ctx=2048, slightly above the 57.9% measured at ctx=4096 in T-0612 Session 24 \u2014 smaller context reduces expert working-set pressure.",
    "Prefill perplexity run was fast on 26B-A4B stock (1606 tok/s prefill) because MoE 4B-active routing is lightweight for the prefill pass compared to dense 31B (269 tok/s)."
  ]
